60","1504":"1504","Fontmell Magna, Dorset, England":"Fontmell Magna, Dorset, England","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1486–about 1560":"about 1486–about 1560","1490–1542":"1490–1542","1504–1601":"1504–1601","1514–1572":"1514–1572","1486–1560":"1486–1560","1572":"1572","1560":"1560","1490":"1490","before 1514":"before 1514","before 1504":"before 1504","1558":"1558","1514":"1514","1601":"1601","1542":"1542","1486":"1486","about 1486":"about 1486","1549":"1549","about 1560":"about 1560","1504":"1504","Fontmell Magna, Dorset, England":"Fontmell Magna, Dorset, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Riggs","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Dorset):","variant of   Ricks   with voicing of /ks/ to /gs/.","variant of   Rigg  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Ricks","meanings":["English: variant of   Rick  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. See also   Rickson  .","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>rixe</i>, <i>rexe</i> (Old English <i>rixe</i>, a West Saxon metathesized form of Old English <i>risc</i>, <i>rysc</i> ‘rush’) wash. The surname probably originally denoted someone who lived where rushes grew, or it may be a habitational name from a place so named, such as Rix (Devon)."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: Bitter; Marion is the French form."],"variants":[{"name":"Marion","meanings":["Originally a medieval French diminutive form of   Marie  , introduced to Britain in the Middle Ages. In some places it was taken as a pet form of   Margaret   or   Margery .  As a male name, it is an altered form of the Continental male name <i>Marian</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>Marianus</i> (from   Marius  ), but is now rarely, if ever, used. It was the birth name of the American film star  John Wayne  (  1907–79 )."]},{"name":"Marcia","meanings":["Often used as a feminine equivalent of   Mark  , but in fact a feminine form of <i>Marcius</i>, itself a derivative of   Marcus .  One  St Marcia  is commemorated in a group with Felix, Luciolus, Fortunatus, and others; another with Zenais, Cyria, and Valeria; and a third with Ariston, Crescentian, Eutychian, Urban, Vitalis, Justus, Felicissimus, Felix, and Symphorosa. None is individually very famous."]}]},{"name":"Babson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: possibly a patronymic from English   Babb  , or perhaps a dissimilated form of   Brabson  , itself a variant of   Brabazon  . It is now very rare in the British Isles."],"variants":[{"name":"Babb","meanings":["Informal pet form of   Barbara ."]}]},{"name":"Noble","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: name derived from the modern English adjective (via Old French from Latin <i>nobilis</i>). The idea behind it may have been to imply aristocratic origin or to suggest qualities of character. In part there may be some influence from the surname, which arose in the Middle Ages from a descriptive nickname in the first sense."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":63,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":72,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parlia